The COVID-19 pandemic has had a severe impact on the Syrian Arab Republic, especially following a 10-year protracted crisis which caused significant damage in rural and urban areas across the country and resulted in a decline in the functionality of basic services as well as a dramatic economic downturn. COVID-19 pandemic spread has significantly increased the vulnerability of the population.
Syria registered its first case of COVID-19 on 22 March 2020. The Ministry of Health (MoH) reported 608 COVID-19 confirmed cases as of 24 July with 35 fatalities and 184 recovered. Although containment and social distancing measures were applied in Syria in March to limit the spread of the virus, it is important to note that the number of cases in July almost doubled the number in June . By 23 December, 10,442  laboratory-confirmed cases had been reported by the MoH . By 29 of December, the total number of infections registered in Syria was 112,43 . According to UN reports, the MoH reported that the increase in COVID-19 cases in Syria has overwhelmed the capacity of local hospitals. 
The repercussions of the conflict in Syria (damage to infrastructure, health, educational, other service institutions and housing, rapid and dynamic demographic change, economic factors aggravated Syrians’ socio-economic situation), as well as the spread of COVID-19, have increased the vulnerability of large segments of the Syrian population, especially in the densely populated areas hosting Internally Displaced People (IDPs) or witnessed returnees movement.  
The above-mentioned factors have affected and contributed to limit the capacities of municipalities/local authorities (materialistic and human resources  gaps) from providing sustainable basic services (WASH, safe water supply, solid waste removal and management, debris removal, hygiene materials and adequate supply of personal protective equipment for cleaning workers) and responding to increased humanitarian needs of population, especially in areas which suffered from large scale damage and areas suffering from increased pressure on basic services and facilities due to hosting IDPs and increased number of returnees.

According to the World Bank, 2023, roughly half of the continent’s population still lack access to electricity, this has gone up in recent years due to population growth outpacing new connections, especially in African urban areas. In places where connection exists, there are challenges of supply inconsistencies and frequent black outs. This stifles industrial growth, curtails economic productivity, and poses challenges to energy sustainability in households and increases overreliance on fuel for energy production in several African homes. Overall, according to Mo Ibrahim Foundation, 2022, electricity shortages cost Africa up to 4% of its GDP per year.

The Lighting an African Family (LAAF): Improving access to clean energy and environmental sustainability in Africa project, will aim to support the increase in access to clean energy for urban communities in select cities in Tanzania, Uganda, Kenya, Nigeria though advocacy and knowledge sharing activities on clean energy with key stakeholders, and establishing the existing gaps in accessing cleaner forms of energy at the end user levels. This will inform the project outputs both at the regional and country levels.
Project Approach

To deliver on the project objectives and achieve its desired impacts at the city, national and regional level, the project will deploy a series of activities, complemented with a communication/visibility plan to amplify awareness on the importance of clean energy. The following outputs will aim to deliver the project objective and the outcomes; 

Output 1: Development of an evidence-based assessment of access to clean energy in Africa

The starting point of the delivery of the project will be the delivery of an evidence-based knowledge product on the state of access to clean energy at the local and national levels. The evidence based assessment will highlight key indicators on the level of clean energy at the National and at the city level, using a targeted community within the urban area as a case study. The indicators that the assessment will target to highlight will be the level of access to both on-grid and off-grid energy supply at the national level, and at the city level i.e end user level. The data will also highlight the gaps in the supply of clean energy and capacity needs by institutional stakeholders in the clean energy sector. At the end of the project, the project will have delivered one assessment report/ knowledge product on the level of access to clean energy in Africa with analysis and case studies from 4 countries and cities i.e Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania and Nigeria.

Output 2: Conduct advocacy and knowledge exchange activities aimed at improving access to clean energy in Africa.

The project will simultaneously conduct advocacy and knowledge sharing activities while developing the assessment reports, this will be achieved through conducting community and institutional stakeholders engagement activities with an aim of collecting data on access to clean energy and sensitizing the wider stakeholders on the need to use and promote the use of clean energy and environmentally friendly activities. In specific, the activities will be complemented with trainings on how to use and maintain solar energy equipment as one of the off grid clean energy sources and entrepreneurial skills for the youth involved in informal trade.
Project implementation and Management

To achieve it’s objective in the four select countries and cities, the project will use an incremental approach in its implementation, it will strive to ensure lessons learnt from the project implementation from the previous city is applied in the next city and so on. This will improve efficiency in project deliverables and overall synergy with the project idea.

UN-Habitat and Shenzhen Poweroak Newener Company Limited, based in China with representation in Africa, based in Nairobi, Kenya will form a joint steering committee that will monitor the progress of the project implementation as well as provide suggestions and decisions in project implementation. The project will also form a technical team that comprises Country leads or Focal points and a regional coordinator that will aim to oversee the smooth implementation of the project activities.

Addis Ababa, Ethiopia’s capital city, is growing rapidly with several unintended consequences such as the increase of informal settlements (due to poverty levels and unplanned urbanisation), horizontal sprawling, inefficient waste management and environmental pollution including air, land, and water pollution., are among other challenges in the city. Unfortunately, informal settlements are often located in inadequate locations, such as in flood-prone areas along the rivers, and highly polluted areas. Wastewater is discharged directly into the water bodies thus compounding river pollution problems highly affecting the life of the residents in the informal settlements along the river and disturbing the ecosystem. For the last fifty years, several industries implemented along the rivers and have also discharged their contaminating chemical wastes into the river systems. Moreover, the soil impermeabilization due to expanding built environment is increasing the frequency and intensity of flood risks in the city after rain events.

The Prime Minister, H.E. Dr Abiy Ahmed, has launched a new national initiative for territorially focused investment in urban renewal, starting with Addis Ababa’s “Beautifying Sheger” project with the involvement of various stakeholders. The project is a multi-stakeholder three-phased approach designed to support its implementation: (1) immediate mobilisation and cleaning of solid waste from the river system; (2) short-term wastewater cleaning and prevention of discharge; and (3) medium to long-term systemic development of the city with distinct objectives.

This landmark project in Addis Ababa covers a stretch of 56km of rivers at an estimated cost of US$1 billion. It aims not only to improve the rivers’ quality but also to mitigate flooding problems increasing in the city and create high quality accessible public spaces, with bicycle paths and walkways along the riversides. There is a wide range of anticipated benefits of the initiative. Indicatively, the project is expected: to improve the social interaction and quality of life of communities living along the river,  improve the cleanness and image of he public space and increase the potential socio-economic activities by promoting sustainable riverside economies and green jobs, to improve environmental conditions, to increase tourism and to provide the city’s residents with quality areas for leisure, sport, culture, art, and recreational activities. This project will run along with the two main river systems of the city.

Promising efforts have already been undertaken by various sectors to overcome the challenges facing the river systems of Addis Ababa, including from the Ministry of Water, Irrigation and Energy (MoWIE) and the Addis Ababa Water and Sewerage Authority in partnership with the World Bank. So far, this Authority has carried out important infrastructure development projects including the construction of municipal wastewater treatment plants with different size sewer lines. Another significant effort is being made through the former Addis Ababa Rivers, Riversides Development (AARRDP) and Climate Change Adaptation Project led by the City Government. A management and development plan were prepared for selected sections of the city’s catchment and a pilot phase is under implementation. Other sectoral offices at the city level are working towards pollution reduction and management, with overlapping mandates.

•	Despite the necessity and clear justification for this project, which can surely have very positive impacts on the city of Addis Ababa, there is a risk to underestimate its overall complexity and the capacity required (not just financial) for its proper planning, design, implementation, and sustainable management and maintenance once concluded. 
•	The project must be planned and designed properly at different scales and with an Integrated Territorial Investment approach in mind. It should be in alignment with the city’s masterplan, not only at the local level (concerned Sub-cities and Weredas) but also at the metropolitan level (the contentious expansion of Addis Ababa into the Oromia Region). Existing urban assets and infrastructure (schools, farms, religious and historical buildings among others) along the riverbanks need to be considered and integrated into the project to keep reasonable implementation costs. Policies, plans, projects, and financial resources should be aligned with the initiative’s main goals, which in turn should address the key local and metropolitan challenges identified via a participatory approach. For this to occur specific plans, guidance notes, feasibility studies, assessments and consultations are needed.

Afghanistan, ranking sixth in the Climate Risk Index, faces a convergence of climate hazards such as droughts, floods, landslides, and extreme heatwaves, aggravating the conditions in a nation already grappling with almost universal poverty after four decades of conflict (Eckstein et al., 2021; OCHA, 2023). Particularly vulnerable are the residents of over 1,000 urban informal settlements, predominantly inhabited by internally displaced persons (IDPs). These settlements, often situated in hazard-prone areas, lack basic services and adequate housing and are frequently targeted for eviction by authorities (REACH Initiative, 2020).

Centring on the urban informal settlements in Herat, Afghanistan's second-largest city, this study delves into the intertwined crises of climate-induced adversities and displacement. Herat, the capital of the drought-affected Western Region, has experienced its third consecutive year of drought in 2023, leading to widespread displacement, economic distress, and food scarcity. Compounding the situation, intense rainfall and resultant flash floods have inflicted fatalities, demolished houses, and decimated livestock and livelihoods. The precariousness of IDP informal settlements is further exacerbated by the recurring threat of eviction, with numerous evictions recorded in 2023 alone.

The project pivots on the hypothesis that insecure housing, land, and property (HLP) rights amplify climate vulnerability in Afghanistan. It aims to evaluate the effectiveness of tools designed to fortify HLP rights and diminish climate susceptibility. Furthermore, the project endeavors to devise a comprehensive strategy to bolster HLP rights, thereby fostering climate-resilient communities.

After the February 2023 earthquakes, UN-Habitat worked with partners to update the previously completed damage assessments and review the existing recovery plans in light of new damage. Based on the existing recovery plans and new damage data, the organisation has been able to identify a range of prioritised interventions to support the recovery of affected neighbourhoods and build their resilience towards future shocks. One such intervention is the water supply to neighbourhoods in eastern Aleppo, which complements UN-Habitat’s earlier interventions and planned future interventions in the area. 

Water is a basic necessity, but the supply of water to eastern Aleppo is currently constrained by a 3 km section of pipeline connecting the Al-Nayrab Pumping Station to several neighbourhood water networks. This pipeline is about 60 years old, and has suffered from lack of maintenance, the 12-year conflict, and most recently the February 2023 earthquakes. The pipeline has now been shut off, and water is instead being supplied by a bypass from another pipeline, which is also affecting delivery to neighbourhoods ordinarily served by this pipeline. Rehabilitation of the identified pipeline is therefore expected to significantly improve water supply to a large service area.

The identified pipeline is located under a main road, alternating between the sidewalk and the vehicle lane. The works would therefore involve excavation of the road, removal of the old pipeline, installation of a new pipeline and restoration of the road environment. These activities would be carried out in close cooperation with Aleppo Municipality and the Water Establishment of the Aleppo Governorate. The restoration of the street after the pipeline works can also be seized upon to improve the road environment, including the widening of sidewalks, planting of trees, placing of benches and replacement of street lighting. The connections between many buildings and the neighbourhood water network have also been damaged or destroyed, and the project will therefore also aim to restore these connections within the target areas.

All works will be carried out by contractors procured through UN-Habitat’s procurement process. UN-Habitat’s hub in Aleppo will regularly monitor the project sites to ensure that works are proceeding according to plan and that agreed safeguards are being adhered to.
The overall objective of the project is to support an integrated recovery and improve the resilience of vulnerable communities in Aleppo. This will be achieved by improving access to household water supply in several neighbourhoods in the eastern part of the city, through the rehabilitation of a damaged supply pipeline and restoration of a number of building connections to the water network, thereby reducing leakage which is currently estimated to be up to 30% in some locations. A sustainable water supply is expected to lead to improved living conditions and health outcomes, as well as contribute to increasing social cohesion by reducing the risk of tension over scarce resources.

The project deliverables:
1.	Rehabilitation of approximately 3 km of water pipeline
2.	Restoration of building water connections
3.	Basic improvements to the street environment during restoration of excavated sections

After more than two years since the official declaration of the end of war against ISIL by the Government of Iraq in late 2017, approximately 1.4 million people are still internally displaced. Many of the internally displaced persons who are originally from Sinjar are caught in protracted displacement, in which they are displaced for almost six years. Studies show that destruction and/or damage to former residences, lack of basic services due to severe damage to public facilities, and the lack of housing, land and property rights documentation are among common obstacles to return. According to the housing damage assessment jointly conducted by UN-Habitat and Shelter Cluster Iraq, there are 4,570 severely damaged or destroyed houses in Sinjar, and as of end of June 2020, approximately 3,000 houses in Sinjar are left without support. While Yazidis are gradually, and fearfully, returning to the retaken areas of Sinjar north of the mountain, the majority of the region’s Yazidis still live under difficult and impoverished conditions in IDP camps scattered throughout the Dohuk region of northern Iraq. Among the displaced people in Iraq, the Yazidis constitute the second largest group after Arab Sunni Muslims. In Sinjar, the original inhabitants were mostly Yazidis with a small number of Arab Sunnis, Arab Shia, Kurds and Christian population. With the recent outbreak of COVID-19, surveys show that more internally displaced persons in Iraq are willing to return to their areas of origin, trying to avoid congested living conditions with inadequate water and sanitation facilities in many of the camps. On the other hand, many conflict-affected areas including Sinjar still have not managed to rehabilitate water, sanitation, hygiene and health facilities that were damaged during the conflict. In order to prevent the ‘secondary displacement’ of those who returned, it is critical to ensure that adequate housing, water, sanitation and hygiene facilities are available in the areas of origin. Based on the findings of an initial rapid assessment, UN-Habitat will take into consideration the needs of all the population in Sinjar to select the most vulnerable community. Through implemented activities, UN-Habitat will target different vulnerable groups of the recent returnees including minorities in Sinjar district. In addition, based on the assessment the project will consider the provision of the support on HLP rights, rehabilitation of the houses based on physical level of damage, rehabilitation of the water, hygiene and sanitation facilities, based on the socio-economic vulnerability of beneficiaries such as Yazidis, including Arabs and Kurds, to promote voluntary and sustainable return and peace building in Sinjar. Aiming at providing land tenure security, adequate housing for returnees, and access to adequate water, sanitation and hygiene facilities, ensure livelihood opportunities and accessibility of various services, including economic activities and legal that will enable business ownership for minorities including women in a conflict-affected district of Sinjar in Iraq, this project addresses the core of the HDP nexus. It carries humanitarian, development and peace components and brings together stakeholders of each of these three fields. First, the humanitarian component is reflected in the urgent assistance of the most vulnerable for the access to housing and water. Second, and as reflected in the UN Secretary Guidance Note on “The United Nations and Land and Conflict”, land is substantial to any kind of conflict and the improvement of tenure security is key for providing sustainable peace. Land tenure security has proved to be a crucial component for achieving sustainable development. The project’s approach reflects the interdependence of the humanitarian, development and peace initiatives, which cannot be treated separately. Finally, recognizing and addressing the consequences of protracted under-investment in water, sanitation and hygiene facilities that underpin urban inequalities in Iraq is essential for prevention of COVID-19 outbreak. Therefore, to facilitate sustainable and dignified returns of vulnerable displaced persons in Iraq, a comprehensive support addressing multiple needs of the returnees and displaced persons is urgently needed. The proposed program will prioritize vulnerable groups including female heads of household, survivors of violence and trauma, victims of military operations and persons with disability/ies, including older persons. Through support for housing, land and property rights, adequate housing and access to water, sanitation and hygiene facilities based on participatory approach engaging women and girls, the project is expected to contribute the SDGs Goal 1: End Poverty, Goal 5: Achieve gender equality and empower all women and girls; Goal 6: Ensure availability and sustainable management of water and sanitation for all, Goal 11: Make cities and human settlements inclusive, safe, res

A joint effort through three key agencies (UN-Habitat, ILO and UNESCO) is instrumental to enhance a multi-dimensional project that tackles strategic actions to provide an inclusive, sustainable and resilient framework of action to kick-start reconstruction with a focus on supporting vulnerable populations and local authorities, in a general effort of piloting recovery solutions and implementation modalities defined by the Government of Mozambique - Reconstruction Cabinet in its Post Disaster Reconstruction Plan (PREPOC). A bottom-up approach with communities and households at the centre of the process, as well as CSOs and NGOs, interacting with local authority and implementing agencies, in a harmonized and coordinated way to pursue its goals.
Economic, environmental and spatial analysis will be carried out to understand in which way each one of the two contexts should be tackled for the reconstruction based on the distribution of their functions, their influence on surrounding areas (urban-rural linkages), in order to plan and extend the concept of resilience to the surrounding environment. In addition, capacity analysis on local construction (heritage restoration, resilient local techniques, materials, etc.) and local production skills (agriculture, fishing, etc.) will provide the baseline for a tailor-made approach of the Project activities and the implementation of participatory methods.
These will feed, in the first project component, the design of two Integrated recovery and reconstruction strategies at district level, with specific action plans for each territories and target neighbourhood, resulting from different types of interventions (Partial and Total Reconstruction, Retrofit, Integrated Recovery of Human Settlements-Existing or New/Resettlement) and operational procedures (“banco de materiais”, community contracts, electronic vouchers) defined by the Reconstruction Cabinet in the PALPOC (Post Disaster Housing Action Plan) and adapted to the particular contexts of Ibo and Buzi District. 
The first project component will begin during the inception phase, in each of the two districts, and will be strategic and transversal to the other three project components, creating the baseline and the shared agreement on priorities and intervention strategy, to serve at the same time the definition of a first Operational Plan for project implementation and the definition of the local recovery framework to be adopted by the district and the Reconstruction Cabinet. This strategy and action plans will be developed in a participatory manner, also following Reconstruction Guidelines, defining consultative bodies such the Local consultative Councils, as well as creating coordination platforms at local authority level, with the aim to implement area-based interventions for resilience building integrating various aspects simultaneously, i.e.: (i) access to basic services (health, education, water, sanitation, waste management) and infrastructure (drainage and roads); (ii) access to secure land tenure; (iii) nature-based solutions and improved public spaces; (iv) affordable housing development; (v) vocational training, income generation activities and/or job creation

According to the UNHCR, there are approximately three million Afghans living in Pakistan, of which 1.32 million are Proof of Registration (PoR) cardholders , approximately 840,000 hold an Afghan Citizen Card (ACC), and an estimated 775,000 are undocumented.   UNHCR 2022 data show that, 53.5% of the registered Afghan refugees are male and 46.5% female. The Provinces of Baluchistan and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa host the vast majority (81%) of the current Afghan population in the country.  There is significant concentration in other major cities including in Islamabad and also in Karachi. Some 31% of refugees live in refugee villages, and the remaining 69% live in urban, peri-urban, and rural areas alongside host communities.  According to IOM, about 20% of the Afghan ACC holders in Pakistan live in refugee villages.
Most Afghan refugees in Pakistan face extremely high levels of multi-dimensional poverty. More than half are counted as extremely poor and ultra-poor. The IOM data show that 31% have temporary/ad hoc employment and 52% live on less than the minimum wage supporting an average family size of six. Afghan refugees and Afghans of other status in Pakistan have several multifaceted protection needs. These include the need for access to registration and documentation to ensure basic rights, facilitate access to services and to mitigate the risk of arrest and detention. 
The health, housing and social-economic status of the host communities in urban slums and the Afghan refugees are generally equally very bad. Respiratory tract infections are prevalent in about half of the Afghan refugee population.  The incidence rates for diarrhoea and dysentery are reported at levels of 3.49 and 1.26 out of 1,000 Afghan refugees.   Housing challenges include tenure insecurity, overcrowding, rising rents, bad infrastructure and basic services.  In both contexts, rising energy costs and the impacts of climate change ,   Where Afghan families have constructed their own homes with local materials, challenges include poor weatherproofing.  Living conditions are particularly wanting for housebound household members, including the elderly and chronically ill, young children and women .  Most Afghan male workers are in lowest-wage and vulnerable jobs as garbage collectors or unskilled building construction labourers.  As Pakistan is experiencing a construction boom, particularly in urban areas, unskilled Afghan miss out on labour opportunities; skilled construction labour can earn 2 times the daily rates of unskilled labour. 
The broader urban development challenges of cities in Pakistan obviously are challenging as well. Planning and service delivery is hampered by high levels of urban population growth and urban expansion. Urban governance capacity and institutional reform have not kept pace. Municipal service delivery including on water, sanitation, waste collection and power supply cannot keep up with urban growth. Especially slum areas, which are anyhow very poorly documented in government statistics, remain chronically underserviced.  Appropriate planning and service delivery requires expertise in analysing urban informal.
